# Canonical fact framing (hard rules)

Portable baseline: `docs/agent-guidelines.md`.

Applies to canonical messaging under `products/`, `framework/`, `use-cases-value-pillars/`, `offerings/`, and `reference/` when the content is canonical positioning. Do not apply to contributor docs such as `README.md`, `CONTRIBUTING.md`, or `.github/`.

Use this rule with `canonical-copy-audience.mdc` and `value-linking-quality.mdc`.

## State shipped facts as current reality

- In canonical body copy, describe shipped capabilities as present reality, for example "PMM has," "PMM includes," or "PMM supports."
- Avoid in-body release framing such as "PMM 3.7 adds," "introduces," or "completes" when the capability is already available.
- Use version or release phrasing only when timing is material to reader decisions, for example upgrade planning, compatibility boundaries, or deprecation windows.

## Disclose engine scope inline

- For engine-limited capabilities, include explicit scope in the same sentence or bullet.
- Preferred pattern: "MongoDB only, not MySQL or PostgreSQL."
- Do not move scope caveats into separate sections when the claim appears earlier in body copy.

## Integrate feature evidence into value copy

- Prefer integrating feature evidence into existing value or outcome bullets.
- Use standalone feature or release bullets only when the feature is itself a top-level positioning pillar for that page.

## Anchor citations at the claim

- Prefer inline citation placement directly on the factual claim in canonical messaging pages.
- Use end-of-section or bottom "Sources" blocks only when a page template explicitly requires that structure.
